Predicting Bad Loans¶

The Federal National Mortgage Association (FNMA), commonly known as Fannie Mae, is a United States government-sponsored enterprise (GSE) and, since 1968, a publicly traded company. Founded in 1938 during the Great Depression as part of the New Deal,the corporation's purpose is to expand the secondary mortgage market by securitizing mortgages in the form of mortgage-backed securities (MBS),allowing lenders to reinvest their assets into more lending and in effect increasing the number of lenders in the mortgage market by reducing the reliance on locally based savings and loan associations (or "thrifts").Its brother organization is the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (FHLMC), better known as Freddie Mac.

On January 26, 2018, Fannie Mae updated its Single-Family Loan Performance credit dataset to:

Primary dataset: Include acquisition data for Q4 2016 and performance data through Q3 2017. Update acquisitions files to reflect any data corrections.

HARP dataset: Include performance data through Q3 2017.

I am goimng to use 2008Q3 data to predict which borrowers are most at risk of defaulting on their mortgage loans.

df_perf = pd.read_csv("2008Q3/Performance_2008Q3.txt", sep="|", names=cols_perf, usecols=[0,15])

In the performance data, we are really only interested in the LoanID and ForeclosureDate columns, as this will give us the borrower identifiaction number and whether or not they ended up defaulting. After reading in the two datasets, we can perform an inner join on the acquisition and performance dataframes using the LoanID column. The resulting dataframe, df, will contain the ForeclosureDate column, and will be our target variable. For clarity, we will also rename this column as Default.

In [4]:
# only keep the last entry for a given loan
df_perf.drop_duplicates(subset='LOAN_ID', keep='last', inplace=True)
In [5]:
df = pd.merge(df_acq, df_perf, on='LOAN_ID', how='inner')
In [6]:
#clear other dataframe from memory
del df_acq, df_perf

Define target variable¶

We introduce a traget variable called BAD_LOAN which indicated if the borrower has defaulted.

For this we will use the FORECLOSURE_DATE column.

Set BAD_LOAN = 0 when FORECLOSURE_DATE value is NaN else to 1

In [7]:
# indicate rows for active loans
df['FORECLOSURE_DATE'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

# indicate rows for defaulted loans
df.loc[df['FORECLOSURE_DATE'] != 0, 'FORECLOSURE_DATE'] = 1

# rename column to a meaningfull name
df.rename(index=str, columns={"FORECLOSURE_DATE": 'BAD_LOAN'}, inplace=True)

Data pre processing¶

Removing some variables based on profiling report

According to profiling data, our dataset has 353277 rows and 27 columns.

The columns containing missing data are:

CO_BORROWER_CREDIT_SCORE has 208664 (59.1%) missing values 
DEBT_TO_INCOME_RATIO has 11339 (3.2%) missing values 
MORTGAGE_INSURANCE_PCT has 277888 (78.7%) missing values 
MORTGAGE_INSURANCE_TYPE has 277888 (78.7%) missing values 
ORIG_COMBINED_LTV has 2 (<1 %)  missing values
NUM_OF_BORROWERS has 55 (<1 %)  missing values
BORROWER_CREDIT_SCORE has 489 (<1 %)  missing values

The columns which should be removed are:

ORIG_COMBINED_LTV is highly correlated with ORIG_LTV ( = 0.96684) 
PRODUCT_TYPE has constant value FRM

Based on above info, we will delete folloing columns from our dataset

MORTGAGE_INSURANCE_PCT

PRODUCT_TYPE

Additionally, LOAN_ID column doesn't contribute to outcome of loan so it also be removed

In [70]:
def process_categorical_cols(df):
    #names of columns with any nan values
    cols_with_nans = df.columns[df.isnull().any()]    
    #make a copy of these columns
    df_with_nans = df[cols_with_nans]
    # drop these columns from processing
    df.drop(cols_with_nans, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # get categorical columns by filtering based on columns of type object i.e string values
    df_cat = df.select_dtypes(include=['object'])
    # get numerical columns (by dropping categorical columns) 
    df_num = df.drop(df_cat.columns, axis=1)
    
    data = pd.DataFrame()
    for i in df_cat.columns:
        tmp = pd.get_dummies(df_cat[i], drop_first=True)
        data = pd.concat([data, tmp], axis=1)
    
    # create a new dataframe containing numerical columns, converted categoricals and columns which has nans 
    df = pd.concat([df_num, data, df_with_nans], axis=1).reset_index(drop=True)
    return df

Impute missing values¶

We have following options to fix missing values:

1. Mean/Median based on distribution of data
2. Random sample from a distribution defined by the present values. 
3. Machine learning algorithm applied to the create values
4. Drop the missing data rows altogether.

Fill the missing values using:

A random forest classifier for strings - A random forest is a meta estimator that fits a number of decision tree classifiers on various sub-samples of the dataset and use averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. The sub-sample size is always the same as the original input sample size but the samples are drawn with replacement.

A random forest regressor for numerical columns - A random forest is a meta estimator that fits a number of classifying decision trees on various sub-samples of the dataset and use averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. The sub-sample size is always the same as the original input sample size but the samples are drawn with replacement.
In [75]:
def imputer(df):
    # columns which have missing values
    columns = df.columns[df.isnull().any()]
    # loop over columns with missing values
    for name in columns:
        # get non null values of this column
        y = df.loc[df[name].notnull(), name].values
        # data having no nulls - used for training
        X_train = df.loc[df[name].notnull()].drop(columns, axis=1).values
        # data having nulls - used for testing
        X_test = df.loc[df[name].isnull()].drop(columns, axis=1).values
        
        if df[name].dtypes == 'object':
            model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=400, max_depth=3)
            model.fit(X_train, y)
            # impute values by predicting them
            df.loc[df[name].isnull(), name] = model.predict(X_test)
        else:
            model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=400, max_depth=3)
            model.fit(X_train, y)
            #impute values by predicting them
            df.loc[df[name].isnull(), name] = model.predict(X_test)
    return df
In [76]:
df = imputer(df)

Balancing proportion of target variable¶

As identified earlier, the the proportion of two values of target variable BAD_LOAN is extremely imbalanced. The bad loan make up for <5% of all borrowers. In such a case, the machine learning algorithm will be biased towards predicting the dominant class. To balance the propostion of good/bad loans, lets use Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE).

In [85]:
from imblearn.combine import SMOTEENN
sm = SMOTEENN()

y = df['BAD_LOAN'].values
X = df.drop(['BAD_LOAN'], axis=1).values

X_resampled, y_resampled = sm.fit_sample(X, y)

Build a model¶

Let fit a random forest classifiers of 200 trees

In [86]:
# perform a 70, 30 split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled, y_resampled, test_size = 0.20, random_state=0)
# random forest classifier with 200 tree,
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=200)
# fit the model
model = model.fit(X_train, y_train)

FN (Bad loan pridicted as good) = 4%

For Federal National Mortgage Association the important metric would be False Negatives i.e. Bad loan pridicted. Ourt model will predict this 4% of the time. One possible reason for this is that could be imblanced data we had to use. Nonetheless, the business to decide if the error is within their appetite.
